# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: http2-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] The standardization effort was supported by the Chrome, Opera, Firefox, Internet Explorer 11, Safari, Amazon Silk, and Edge browsers.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] Most major browsers had added HTTP/2 support by the end of 2015.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] About 97% of web browsers used have the capability (and 100% of "tracked desktop" web browsers).
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] As of July 2023, 36% (after topping out at just over 50%) of the top 10 million websites support HTTP/2.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] Its successor is HTTP/3, a major revision that builds on the concepts established by HTTP/2.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] The changes do not require any changes to how existing web applications work, but new applications can take advantage of new features for increased speed.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] HTTP/2 leaves all of HTTP/1.1's high-level semantics, such as methods, status codes, header fields, and URIs, the same.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] What is new is how the data is framed and transported between the client and the server.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] Websites that are efficient minimize the number of requests required to render an entire page by minifying (reducing the amount of code and packing smaller pieces of code into bundles, without reducing its ability to function) resources such as images and scripts.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] However, minification is not necessarily convenient nor efficient and may still require separate HTTP connections to get the page and the minified resources.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] HTTP/2 allows the server to "push" content, that is, to respond with data for more queries than the client requested.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] This allows the server to supply data it knows a web browser will need to render a web page, without waiting for the browser to examine the first response, and without the overhead of an additional request cycle.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] Additional performance improvements in the first draft of HTTP/2 (which was a copy of SPDY) come from multiplexing of requests and responses to avoid some of the head-of-line blocking problem in HTTP 1 (even when HTTP pipelining is used), header compression, and prioritization of requests.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] However, as HTTP/2 runs on top of a single TCP connection, there is still potential for head-of-line blocking to occur if TCP packets are lost or delayed in transmission.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] HTTP/2 no longer supports HTTP/1.1's chunked transfer encoding mechanism, as it provides its own, more efficient mechanisms for data streaming.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] SPDY (pronounced like "speedy") was a previous HTTP-replacement protocol developed by a research project spearheaded by Google.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] Primarily focused on reducing latency, SPDY uses the same TCP pipe but different protocols to accomplish this reduction.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] The basic changes made to HTTP/1.1 to create SPDY included "true request pipelining without FIFO restrictions, message framing mechanism to simplify client and server development, mandatory compression (including headers), priority scheduling, and even bi-directional communication".
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] The HTTP Working Group considered Google's SPDY protocol, Microsoft's HTTP Speed+Mobility proposal (SPDY based), and Network-Friendly HTTP Upgrade.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] In July 2012, Facebook provided feedback on each of the proposals and recommended HTTP/2 be based on SPDY.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] The initial draft of HTTP/2 was published in November 2012 and was based on a straight copy of SPDY.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] The biggest difference between HTTP/1.1 and SPDY was that each user action in SPDY is given a "stream ID", meaning there is a single TCP channel connecting the user to the server.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] SPDY split requests into either control or data, using a "simple to parse binary protocol with two types of frames".
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] SPDY showed evident improvement over HTTP, with a new page load speedup ranging from 11% to 47%.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] The development of HTTP/2 used SPDY as a jumping-off point.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] Among the many detailed differences between the protocols, the most notable is that HTTP/2 uses a fixed Huffman code-based header compression algorithm, instead of SPDY's dynamic stream-based compression.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] This helps to reduce the potential for compression oracle attacks on the protocol, such as the CRIME attack.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] On February 9, 2015, Google announced plans to remove support for SPDY in Chrome in favor of support for HTTP/2.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] This took effect starting with Chrome 51.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] HTTP/2 is defined for both HTTP URIs (without TLS encryption, a configuration which is abbreviated as **h2c**) and HTTPS URIs (over TLS using ALPN extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required, a configuration which is abbreviated as **h2**).
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] Although the standard itself does not require usage of encryption, all major client implementations (Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Internet Explorer, Opera, Safari) have stated they will only support HTTP/2 over TLS, which makes encryption de facto mandatory.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] The FreeBSD and Varnish developer Poul-Henning Kamp asserts that the standard was prepared on an unrealistically short schedule, ruling out any basis for the new HTTP/2 other than the SPDY protocol and resulting in other missed opportunities for improvement.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] Kamp criticizes the protocol itself for being inconsistent and having needless, overwhelming complexity.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] He also states that the protocol violates the protocol layering principle, for example by duplicating flow control that belongs in the transport layer (TCP).
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] He also suggested that the new protocol should have removed HTTP Cookies, introducing a breaking change.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] Initially, some members of the Working Group tried to introduce an encryption requirement in the protocol.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] Critics stated that encryption has non-negligible computing costs and that many HTTP applications actually have no need for encryption and their providers have no desire to spend additional resources on it.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] Encryption proponents have stated that this encryption overhead is negligible in practice.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] Poul-Henning Kamp has criticized the IETF for hastily standardizing Google's SPDY prototype as HTTP/2 due to political considerations.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] In the end the Working Group did not reach consensus over the mandatory encryption, although most client implementations require it, which makes encryption a *de facto* requirement.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] The HTTP/2 protocol also faced criticism for not supporting opportunistic encryption, a measure against passive monitoring similar to the STARTTLS mechanism that has long been available in other Internet protocols like SMTP.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] Critics have stated that the HTTP/2 proposal goes in violation of IETF's own RFC 7258 "Pervasive Monitoring Is an Attack", which also has a status of Best Current Practice 188.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] RFC7258/BCP188 mandates that pervasive monitoring be considered as an attack, and protocols designed by IETF should take steps to protect against passive monitoring (for example, through the use of opportunistic encryption).
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] A number of specifications for opportunistic encryption of HTTP/2 have been provided, of which draft-nottingham-http2-encryption was adopted as an official work item of the working group, leading to the publication of RFC 8164 in May 2017.
[src:http2-protocol/hpack] This head-of-line blocking in HTTP/2 is now widely regarded as a design flaw, and much of the effort behind QUIC and HTTP/3 has been devoted to reduce head-of-line blocking issues.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] In push technology, clients can express their preferences for certain types of information or data, typically through a process known as the publish–subscribe model.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] In this model, a client "subscribes" to specific information channels hosted by a server.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] When new content becomes available on these channels, the server automatically sends, or "pushes," this information to the subscribed client.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Under certain conditions, such as restrictive security policies that block incoming HTTP requests, push technology is sometimes simulated using a technique called polling.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] In these cases, the client periodically checks with the server to see if new information is available, rather than receiving automatic updates.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Synchronous conferencing and instant messaging are examples of push services.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Chat messages and sometimes files are pushed to the user as soon as they are received by the messaging service.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Both decentralized peer-to-peer programs (such as WASTE) and centralized programs (such as IRC or XMPP) allow pushing files, which means the sender initiates the data transfer rather than the recipient.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Email may also be a push system: SMTP is a push protocol (see Push e-mail).
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] However, the last step—from mail server to desktop computer—typically uses a pull protocol like POP3 or IMAP.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Modern e-mail clients make this step seem instantaneous by repeatedly polling the mail server, frequently checking it for new mail.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] The IMAP protocol includes the IDLE command, which allows the server to tell the client when new messages arrive.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] The original BlackBerry was the first popular example of push-email in a wireless context.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Another example is the PointCast Network, which was widely covered in the 1990s.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] It delivered news and stock market data as a screensaver.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Both Netscape and Microsoft integrated push technology through the Channel Definition Format (CDF) into their software at the height of the browser wars, but it was never very popular.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Other uses of push-enabled web applications include software updates distribution ("push updates"), market data distribution (stock tickers), online chat/messaging systems (webchat), auctions, online betting and gaming, sport results, monitoring consoles, and sensor network monitoring.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] The Web push proposal of the Internet Engineering Task Force is a simple protocol using HTTP version 2 to deliver real-time events, such as incoming calls or messages, which can be delivered (or "pushed") in a timely fashion.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] The protocol consolidates all real-time events into a single session which ensures more efficient use of network and radio resources.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] A single service consolidates all events, distributing those events to applications as they arrive.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] This requires just one session, avoiding duplicated overhead costs.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Web Notifications are part of the W3C standard and define an API for end-user notifications.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] A notification allows alerting the user of an event, such as the delivery of an email, outside the context of a web page.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] As part of this standard, Push API is fully implemented in Chrome, Firefox, and Edge, and partially implemented in Safari as of February 2023.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] HTTP server push (also known as HTTP streaming) is a mechanism for sending unsolicited (asynchronous) data from a web server to a web browser.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] HTTP server push can be achieved through any of several mechanisms.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] As a part of HTML5 the Web Socket API allows a web server and client to communicate over a full-duplex TCP connection.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Generally, the web server does not terminate a connection after response data has been served to a client.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] The web server leaves the connection open so that if an event occurs (for example, a change in internal data which needs to be reported to one or multiple clients), it can be sent out immediately; otherwise, the event would have to be queued until the client's next request is received.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Most web servers offer this functionality via CGI (e.g., Non-Parsed Headers scripts on Apache HTTP Server).
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] The underlying mechanism for this approach is chunked transfer encoding.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Another mechanism is related to a special MIME type called `multipart/x-mixed-replace`, which was introduced by Netscape in 1995.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Web browsers interpret this as a document that changes whenever the server pushes a new version to the client.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] It is still supported by Firefox, Opera, and Safari today, but it is ignored by Internet Explorer and is only partially supported by Chrome.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] It can be applied to HTML documents, and also for streaming images in webcam applications.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] The WHATWG Web Applications 1.0 proposal includes a mechanism to push content to the client.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] On September 1, 2006, the Opera web browser implemented this new experimental system in a feature called "Server-Sent Events".
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] In this technique, the server takes advantage of persistent HTTP connections, leaving the response perpetually "open" (i.e., the server never terminates the response), effectively fooling the browser to remain in "loading" mode after the initial page load could be considered complete.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] The server then periodically sends snippets of JavaScript to update the content of the page, thereby achieving push capability.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] By using this technique, the client doesn't need Java applets or other plug-ins in order to keep an open connection to the server; the client is automatically notified about new events, pushed by the server.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] One serious drawback to this method, however, is the lack of control the server has over the browser timing out; a page refresh is always necessary if a timeout occurs on the browser end.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Long polling is itself not a true push; long polling is a variation of the traditional polling technique, but it allows emulating a push mechanism under circumstances where a real push is not possible, such as sites with security policies that require rejection of incoming HTTP requests.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] With long polling, the client requests to get more information from the server exactly as in normal polling, but with the expectation that the server may not respond immediately.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] If the server has no new information for the client when the poll is received, then instead of sending an empty response, the server holds the request open and waits for response information to become available.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Once it does have new information, the server immediately sends an HTTP response to the client, completing the open HTTP request.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Upon receipt of the server response, the client often immediately issues another server request.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] In this way the usual response latency (the time between when the information first becomes available and the next client request) otherwise associated with polling clients is eliminated.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] This technique, used by chat applications, makes use of the XML Socket object in a single-pixel Adobe Flash movie.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Under the control of JavaScript, the client establishes a TCP connection to a unidirectional relay on the server.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] The relay server does not read anything from this socket; instead, it immediately sends the client a unique identifier.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Next, the client makes an HTTP request to the web server, including this identifier with it.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] The web application can then push messages addressed to the client to a local interface of the relay server, which relays them over the Flash socket.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] The advantage of this approach is that it appreciates the natural read-write asymmetry that is typical of many web applications, including chat, and as a consequence it offers high efficiency.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Since it does not accept data on outgoing sockets, the relay server does not need to poll outgoing TCP connections *at all*, making it possible to hold open tens of thousands of concurrent connections.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] In this model, the limit to scale is the TCP stack of the underlying server operating system.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] In services such as cloud computing, to increase reliability and availability of data, it is usually pushed (replicated) to several machines.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] For example, the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS) makes 2 extra copies of any object stored.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] RGDD focuses on efficiently casting an object from one location to many while saving bandwidth by sending minimal number of copies (only one in the best case) of the object over any link across the network.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] For example, Datacast is a scheme for delivery to many nodes inside data centers that relies on regular and structured topologies and DCCast is a similar approach for delivery across data centers.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] A push notification is a message that is "pushed" from a back-end server or application to a user interface, e.g. mobile applications or desktop applications.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Apple introduced push notifications for iPhone in 2009, and in 2010 Google released "Google Cloud to Device Messaging" (superseded by Google Cloud Messaging and then by Firebase Cloud Messaging).
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Push notifications are mainly divided into two approaches, local notifications and remote notifications.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] For local notifications, the application schedules the notification with the local device's OS.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] The application sets a timer in the application itself, provided it is able to continuously run in the background.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] When the event's scheduled time is reached, or the event's programmed condition is met, the message is displayed in the application's user interface.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Remote notifications are handled by a remote server.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Under this scenario, the client application needs to be registered on the server with a unique key (e.g., a UUID or Apple *Device Token*).
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] The server then transmits the message against the unique key to deliver it to the client via an agreed client/server protocol such as HTTP or XMPP.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] When the push notification arrives at the client, it can cause the display of short notifications or messages, set badges on application icons, blink or continuously light up the notification LED, or play alert sounds to attract user's attention.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Push notifications are usually used by applications to bring information to users' attention.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] Real-time push notifications may raise privacy issues since they can be used to bind virtual identities of social network pseudonyms to the real identities of the smartphone owners.
[src:http2-protocol/server-push] The use of unnecessary push notifications for promotional purposes has been criticized as an example of attention theft.
